docs.abstract: A look back at maybe the one good thing to come out of lockdown: getting to know your neighbors.
docs.snippet: A look back at maybe the one good thing to come out of lockdown: getting to know your neighbors.
docs.lead_paragraph: Impromptu concerts from the fire escape. Food relief efforts staged on the sidewalk in front of a church. Friends spread out on the stoop and drinking tallboys. As the city reopens, New Yorkers emerging from quarantine might feel a bit nostalgic for the socially distant bonds they formed outside their homes. From the first days of the lockdown in April, through the advent of legal drinking in front of restaurants, to protests in the streets for racial justice, The Times collected stories of how neighbors across the five boroughs handled the shutdown and, at times, came together.

headline.main: How the Stoop and the Sidewalk Helped New Yorkers Stay Sane

docs.lead_paragraph: They were held for more than a day in crowded New York City jail cells, some without masks. Cheerios and food wrappers littered the floor. In one holding pen, detainees spread tissue over a clogged toilet to try to reduce the stench emanating from it.

headline.main: Despite Virus, Hundreds Arrested in Unrest Are Held in Cramped Jails
headline.print_headline: Detained Protesters and Looters Grind Through a Clogging Justice System

docs.lead_paragraph: Kenneth Timmons, who works for a federal government agency in Houston, said the first thing he usually does before every Juneteenth is take the day off work. Mr. Timmons usually invites friends over to cook and eat together.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Los Angeles chef Josef Centeno woke up early Saturday morning, to find piles of smashed glass and scrawls of graffiti at his downtown restaurants. Like so many businesses, his Bar Amá and Bäco Mercat had been vandalized during protests overnight.

docs.abstract: Our city is a coronavirus hot spot. We were only trying to protect him.
docs.snippet: Our city is a coronavirus hot spot. We were only trying to protect him.
docs.lead_paragraph: Our 16-year-old son asked us if he could attend a Black Lives Matter protest march in our city, a Covid-19 hot spot. We said no. We decided it was too dangerous in terms of coronavirus risk and possible violence. He sneaked out of the apartment and went anyway. He claims he wore a mask and was socially distant the whole time, but we’re not sure whether to believe him or how to punish him. Any advice?

headline.main: We Told Our Son Not to Protest. He Did Anyway. Now What?

docs.abstract: Two prominent firms, Lloyd’s of London and Greene King, have acknowledged their ties to the slave trade and pledged to make amends.
docs.snippet: Two prominent firms, Lloyd’s of London and Greene King, have acknowledged their ties to the slave trade and pledged to make amends.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Britain’s uneasy confrontation with its racist history moved from statues in town squares to corporate boardrooms this week, as two prominent British firms, Lloyd’s of London and Greene King, announced they would make amends for their involvement in the slave trade in the 18th and 19th centuries.

headline.main: Britain Grapples With Its Racist Past, From the Town Square to the Boardroom
headline.print_headline: 2 Prominent British Firms Say They’ll Pay Reparations for Slavery
